        ],
        "order": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_1",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Kiran Kedlaya and Lenny Ng",
        "bbox": [
          0.4003759429718004,
          0.11627907003802782,
          0.607142857466796,
          0.13081395312088695
        ],
        "order": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_2",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A-1 Yes, it does follow. Let P be any point in the plane. Let ABCD be any square with center P. Let E,F,G, H be the midpoints of the segments AB, BC, CD, DA, respectively. The function f must satisfy the equations",
        "bbox": [
          0.09586466560150368,
          0.16715116302252403,
          0.4906015095808188,
          0.22395833310452995
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_15",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A-3 The limit is 0; we will show this by checking that dn = 0 for all n ≥ 3. Starting from the given matrix, add the third column to the first column; this does not change the determinant. However, thanks to the identity cosx + cosy =2 cos *7} cos *Z', the resulting matrix has the form",
        "bbox": [
          0.5225564033571184,
          0.16715116302252403,
          0.9210526271691972,
          0.2519451485315607
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_3",
        "observed_type": "formula",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.1766917257813324,
          0.23834325385279623,
          0.4003759420864661,
          0.3430232558143538
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_16",
        "observed_type": "formula",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.5827067692380932,
          0.2643863415334954,
          0.81203007180954,
          0.3038194442212865
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_17",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "with the first column being a multiple of the second. Hence dn = 0.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5582706840012449,
          0.34300595242879106,
          0.9191729340438677,
          0.37080932157812224
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "If we add the last four equations, then subtract the first equation and twice the second equation, we obtain 0 = 4f(P), whence f(P) = 0.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12593985598307048,
          0.3561046510279427,
          0.49060151260400175,
          0.3998015874632723
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_18",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Remark. Another way to draw the same conclusion is to observe that the given matrix is the sum of the two rank 1 matrices Ajk = cos(j - 1)ncosk and B jk = - sin(j - 1)nsink, and so has rank at most 2. One can also use the matrices Ajk = e'(i-1)n+k), B jk = eilj-1)n+k",
        "bbox": [
          0.556346361536796,
          0.37645348882536567,
          0.9210526404235507,
          0.4652710074447214
        ],
        "order": 9
      }
    ]
  },
  {
